[2]
Date: Mon 27 Jun 2011
From: Mary Ann Benitez <maryann.benitez@gmail.com> [edited]


This afternoon (Mon 27 Jun 2011) the Controller of the Centre for
Health Protection Thomas Tsang Ho-fair held a press stand-up on the
latest situation and disclosed the serotype of the strains, as
follows: tests of 97 bacterial samples show the dominant strain to be
M12: 50 of them belong to M12, 16 have M1, and 8 are M28.

70-80 percent of M12 has the new mutated gene (referred to in our
earlier report), which is antibiotic-resistant, while some of the M1
have it as well. No details [were given] on M28.

--
Mary Ann Benitez
<maryann.benitez@gmail.com>

[The Hong Kong outbreak group A streptococcal isolates are
predominantly serotype M12, with smaller numbers of M1 and M28. M1 and
M12 are known to be prevalent serotypes in several regions, such as
North America and Taiwan. Serotype M28 isolates are overrepresented
among cases of puerperal sepsis and neonatal group A streptococcal
infections, but they also cause other types of invasive infections and
pharyngitis (http://expasy.org/sprot/hamap/STRPM.html). However,
further genotypic characterization of outbreak isolates by molecular
methods such as multilocus sequence typing, ribotyping, pulsed-field
gel electrophoresis (PFGE), and random amplified polymorphic DNA
(RAPD) analysis will be necessary to see if there are common outbreak
strains. For further discussion of group A _Streptococcus_ genotyping,
see ProMED-mail post Streptococcus group A, scarlet fever - China
(04): (HK, MO) 20110624.1937.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Hong Kong and neighboring
China and Macau can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/0_xc. -
Mod.ML]
